<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Baja Highway 1 — Loreto to La Paz</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Baja Highway 1 — Loreto to La Paz</h2><p><i>Baja California Sur, Mexico · MEX-1</i></p><p><b>Sea of Cortés to Sierra de la Giganta to the Pacific approach — 360 km of cardón cactus and turquoise bays.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>351 km (218 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>5–6 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>November–April (summer heat is brutal; chubasco storms August–October)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Livestock at night (genuinely never drive after dark), narrow shoulders, occasional military checkpoints (routine, polite), no fuel for 150 km between Cd. Constitución and the south</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>532</td></tr></table><hr><p>Mexican Federal Highway 1 runs the entire 1,700 km Baja peninsula. The Loreto-to-La Paz stretch may be its most varied: the road leaves the Sea of Cortés at Loreto, climbs into the Sierra de la Giganta with cardón cacti taller than telephone poles, drops to a desert agricultural valley around Constitución, then rejoins the sea at La Paz, gateway to the southern beach country. Loreto was the first Spanish mission in the Californias (1697); the cobblestone streets and 1697 mission stones are still there. Drive only in daylight — Mexican highways at night and free-roaming cattle do not mix. Eat fish tacos.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Loreto Mission</b> — Misión Nuestra Señora de Loreto Conchó, founded 1697 — the first permanent Spanish settlement in the Californias and the mother of all 27 missions of Baja and Alta California.</li><li><b>Misión San Javier (spur)</b> — 1699 stone mission, 36 km up a paved-now-mostly road into the Sierra. The most beautiful surviving Jesuit mission in Baja.</li><li><b>Puerto Escondido / Bay of Loreto NP</b> — Protected harbor and marine park; blue, fin, and humpback whales pass January–March. Sea-kayak launches to Isla del Carmen.</li><li><b>Ciudad Constitución</b> — Agricultural service town — citrus, dates, alfalfa pumped from the fossil aquifer below. Last reliable fuel before the 150 km empty stretch south.</li><li><b>El Cien</b> — Literally 'kilometer 100' — a Pemex station and one taco stand on a long, lonely highway. Photographically iconic of remote Baja driving.</li><li><b>La Paz Malecón</b> — 5 km waterfront promenade along the Bahía de La Paz. Sunset over the bay is genuinely one of the best in Mexico. Whale-shark snorkeling Oct–Apr from local pangas.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
